    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-05-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-05-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="450"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d450">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Conference files, lot 60D 627, <gloss
                        target="#t_CF1">CF</gloss> 286</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Special Adviser to the
                        United States Delegation</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_TRL1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Thurston</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date"
                            when="1954-05-07">May 7, 1954</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>Subject:</head>
                    <item>Turkish Views on Korean and Indochinese Questions</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>Participants:</head>
                    <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_AC1">Acikalin</persName>, Turkish
                        Delegation</item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BT1">Benler</persName>, Turkish
                        Delegation</item>
                    <item>General <persName corresp="#p_SWB1">Smith</persName>, US Delegation</item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_TRL1">Ray L. Thurston</persName>, US Delegation</item>
                </list>
                <p>[Here follows the first portion of the conversation dealing with the Korean phase
                    of the Geneva Conference.]</p>
                <p>After a preliminary remark to the effect that Turkey was not a participant in the
                    Indochinese discussions, <persName corresp="#p_AC1">Acikalin</persName> asked
                    General <persName corresp="#p_SWB1">Smith</persName> how things were going on
                    that side. General <persName corresp="#p_SWB1">Smith</persName> emphasized that
                    the problem at this stage was primarily one for the French and the Associated
                    States. The US has not yet formulated a definite position, but it was our
                    thought that we might be able to save Laos and Cambodia in any event. In his
                    remarks the Turkish delegate took a very pessimistic line on Indochina and with
                    fervent gestures to a map of the Far East on the wall asked how he could contain
                    the Communist march on Southeast Asia once a Communist state obtained control of
                    a part of Indochina. He was critical of the French on the colonial <pb
                        facs="0742" n="716" xml:id="pg_716"/> aspect and talked about the importance
                    of the free Asian nations having a role to play. He referred to the color
                    consciousness of the Asians as a factor we had to take into account.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_TRL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Ray L. Thurston</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
